body.description: The Ml09 is an evolution and variation of the premium Mini-ITX HTPC case, The Milo Ml06. With external Dimension unchanged at 7 liters, the Ml09 rearranged internal layout provides a crucial second expansion slot for support of more powerful low-profile discrete graphics card or expansion card that are two slots wide. For users that wish to build with a more robust GPU or tuner card in console/dvr-like form factor to game or for multimedia content recording, the Ml09 is a great starting point

manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: SilverStone's Milo Case Series SilverStone's Milo (ML) line of cases appeals to home theater PC aficionados, or anyone who simply wants a slim, sleek PC on their desktop. SilverStone ML09 The ML09 offers a modern take on the mini-ITX format, providing ample room for low-profile coolers and a dual-slot, low-profile expansion card, along with an SFX-class power supply. Notable features include: A total volume of just 7 liters! Stylish front panel with mirror finish Space for four 2.5" hard drives Support for slim-line optical drive
A Compact Case Full of Features: Includes one 120mm fan Supports dual-slot low-profile graphics card Supports up to four 2.5" HDD/SSDs

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on July 23, 2022
reviews.reviewText: Perfect size for my needs but even with the smallest SFX power supply the SSD drive cage caused the power cables to almost have to bend impossibly to the right. Drive cage needs to be about half the width it is for a comfortable PSU install.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 10, 2021
reviews.reviewText: This case is outstanding for a small ITX build. The case is the size of a traditional audio receiver, and it has room for a mini-itx board and SFX PSU. I put the Asrock A520M-ITX/ac board in it with 32GB RAM and a Ryzen 7 5700G. I had to update the BIOS on the board before it would recognize the processor, but otherwise was a great build. I am using an NVME drive, so the 4x 2.5" drive bay is not installed. If it were, it would be a tight fit with my EVGA SuperNOVA 450 GM PSU (which has modular cabling). The positioning of the PSU and the motherboard power connectors was ideal for the short modular cables that come with that power supply.I am very happy with the space and the vents in this case. Overall, this is a great case for a small system.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on November 24, 2021
reviews.reviewText: Was nice to build in. Overall I really like it. Provided m.2 screw was too small and didn't secure my drive well enough. I also was able to fit a slightly bigger PSU in it but sacrificed the drive cages. If you're looking for a smaller build chassis, I'd say give this one a go.
